      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"chaotic\" behavior can be frustrating for on-call teams.\n\nOne potential edge case to investigate is the use of \"keep-alive\" connections in the driver. Keep-alive connections can sometimes lead to unexpected behavior, especially if the underlying network is unstable or if there are issues with the connection pool itself.\n\nAnother possibility is that the app is using a technique called \"connection pooling with a timeout\" which can sometimes lead to unexpected behavior. When a connection times out, the pool may try to reuse the connection, but if the underlying connection is still in a \"dead\" state, it can cause the pool to oscillate wildly.\n\nAdditionally, some databases may have issues with \"connection caching\" which can cause the pool to become overutilized and lead to unpredictable behavior. Connection caching is a technique used to improve performance by caching connections to frequently accessed databases.\n\nIt's also worth investigating the use of \"lazy loading\" or \"just-in-time\" loading of database connections. If the connections are being loaded on demand, it can sometimes lead to unexpected behavior, especially if the underlying database is experiencing high loads or if there are issues with the connection pool itself.\n\nLastly, it's worth noting that some databases may have issues with \"connection draining\"",
